sentence: Fatima Kline (115.5) vs.

Melissa Martinez (116) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Kline (-1450); Martinez (+800) Round 1 The UFC is back in everyone's life again, starting up a series of consecutive Saturdays that will run straight to Sept.
Along the way, there will be stops in New Orleans, Abu Dhabi, Chicago, Paris, Perth, and yes, even the Apex a couple timesâbut not as many there as usual.
This marathon of UFC-owned weekends commences with Fight Night fare offering extremely limited goods for ranked-fighter aficionados.
Nevertheless, violence is primed to ensue based on this matchmaking.
The first of 12 tonight goes down in the women's strawweight division, between two ladies that might make referee Jimmy Neely work for it all 15 minutes.
Kline (7-1, 1-1 UFC) has found her home at 115 pounds, and she will try to be the kryptonite to "Super Mely" Martinez (8-1, 1-1 UFC).

They do not touch gloves to get things going. (function (v,i) { let screenWidth = i.innerWidth; if (screenWidth <= 400) { document.getElementById('adViAi').style.display = 'none'; return; } var scp = v.createElement('script'), config = { ChannelID: '0nqr3w5ff', AdUnitType: '2', PublisherID: '256607409443141', PlacementID: 'pltU2JIgmaTXI9XW18z', DivID: '', IAB_Category: 'IAB17', Keywords: '', Language: 'en-us', BG_Color: '', Text_Color: '', Font: '', FontSize: '', }; scp.src='https://s.vi-serve.com/tagLoader.js'; scp.type = 'text/javascript'; scp.async = true; scp.onload = function() { i[btoa('video intelligence start')].init(config); }; (v.getElementsByTagName('head')[0] || v.documentElement.appendChild(v.createElement('head'))).appendChild(scp); })(document, window); Advertisement The New Yorker introduces herself with a couple kicks, first aimed low and then towards the dome.
Martinez hops along the outer edge of the cage to avoid the distant strikes, with Kline utilizing the most of her slight reach advantage.
The kicks are flustering "Super Mely" early, who is trying to find her footing and timing but is mostly circling away.
The crowd is quick to grow restless watching this strawweight sparring match, although it is mostly Kline leading the dance.
She headhunts her way in behind a kick, looping a lead right hook after it a few times.
Kline digs a few kicks to the midsection when peppering Martinez from the outside, and Martinez gives her one back to think about.
Kline pokes and prods with an effective jab, setting up short combos and the occasional right hook.
One such blow briefly wobbles Martinez' legs, but she is able to shake it out and push out a front kick to the chest.
Her head is snapped back by punches from "The Archangel," and she retaliates with a high kick that bangs into the guard.
Kline digs a kick to the body and ducks away from the counters, and she recklessly bowls her way in and gets tagged with a left hook.
Martinez sits down in a pair of power punches, and Kline rolls with them and continues pressing forward.
Martinez bounces off the wall, and Kline is right in her face with jab after sharp jab.
Martinez gets off a partial low kick, and she whiffs on the punch offering after it.
Martinez pushes out with a side kick, and the moment Kline grabs it, she extends her leg to jam her foot in Kline's face.
Kline shrugs it off and swings her way forward, getting off two punches and fighting off a trip as the round concludes.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Kline Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Kline Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Kline Round 2 The pace is not overly intense to get started in the second stanza, with Kline coming out of her corner to serve as the initial aggressor.
She uses kicks to work her way in, potshotting the Mexican woman until rushing forward to tie her up or perhaps pursue a takedown.
When Kline jams Martinez up against the wall, Kline delivers a solid number of knees to the body.
Martinez splits and eats an uppercut on the way out, and both women let their hands fly in a fast exchange.
Martinez boots Kline upside the head, and Kline no-sells it completely and chips at the welted leg of her opponent.
Both women switch stances, and Kline gets behind her jab.
Kline uses her jab to meander forward, catching a kick to lob a right hand over the top that misses the mark by a matter of inches.
She slips and rips a few times, targeting the head and body indiscriminately.
Martinez throws hard, even clipping Kline with a clean left hand, and she decides to put more oomph behind her shots.
Kline eats a hard overhand right working her way in, where she takes some of the sting out of those blows by not giving Martinez any space to toss them.
Martinez fights with all her might to break out of the clinch, succeeding and following with a rifling left hand down the pipe.
Kline swings back with a vengeance, and Martinez turns her head either direction to sway just enough away from them.
Kline knows that Martinez will keep throwing kicks, and she takes advantage of one and hunts for a trip after a single-leg takedown.
Martinez hops to put her back to the wall, and the horn sounds.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Kline Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Kline Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Kline Round 3 The strawweights meet in the center of the cage, not touching gloves but instead getting right to business.
Kline surges forward behind a head kick, driving Martinez back with a subsequent flurry of fists.
Martinez dips back and scoops a shovel uppercut to the body.
Kline takes a moment before probing back out with her jab, and Martinez is a flamethrower with her fists flying every counter opportunity.
Kline chases Martinez around, steps in with a knee to the body and recoils it when Martinez snatches it in the air.
Kline bends over and lets loose a big left hand, and she is able to get in on Martinez a second time before any counter is aimed her way.
They punch at the same time, and Kline has her foot on the gas.

Commentator Laura Sanko suggests that as Kline is advancing and landing body shots, it would be in her best interest to go high with a lead-leg kick.As if Kline was listening, "The Archangel" releases a devastating head kick that smashes square into the jaw, and Martinez goes down in a crumpled heap.

Kline is not finished yet, and she lords over the fallen woman and bludgeons her with a stream of fiery fists until Neely has no choice but to wave things off.The crowd goes nuts, elated that this otherwise straightforward strawweight kickboxing tilt ended so gloriously violent.
Just like that, Kline is most likely going to find a number next to her name come Monday.
She just opened one heck of a birthday present.
The Official Result Fatima Kline def.
Melissa Martinez R3 2:36 via TKO (Head Kick and Punches)
Mitch Ramirez (156) vs.

Mike Davis (155.25) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Davis (-1000); Ramirez (+650) Round 1 Depending on your book of choice, this lightweight match had either the greatest betting disparity of any bout tonight, or it is second place only to Kline, who ranged from -950 to -1500.
When the dust settles, one of the two men will have lost two in a row for the first time.
Nevertheless, massive underdog Ramirez (8-2, 0-1 UFC) is ready to put Davis (11-3, 4-2 UFC) on that losing streak.
Finish rates of 82% and 87%, respectively, mean that referee Justin Brown should be ready to intervene at a moment's notice.
The lightweights touch 'em up.
Davis rushes forward behind his jab, and Ramirez knocks him back with a left hook.
Ramirez is swinging for the bleachers, and Davis ducks it, grabs hold of Ramirez from behind and nearly sets up standing guillotine choke as they scramble.
Ramirez breaks out of it, and he lets fly a number of quick kicks.
Davis wants to implement his wrestling, and he snatches up a single-leg takedown and lifts "The Fight Stalker" in the air and slams him down to the mat.
A discombobulated Ramirez allows Davis to take his back when he turns to his knees, and Davis wraps his right arm under the chin.
There is only one arm on the rear-naked choke, with Ramirez keeping two-on-one wrist control on the other.
Ramirez gets out of the choke and showboats, signaling the heavy metal horns while sticking his tongue out.
Thankfully for the former inmate that walked out to "Folsom Prison Blues," he does not have a "Hello Japan" moment as Davis cannot resecure the choke.
"Beast Boy" locks down the body triangle, but he is unable to get off much more meaningful offense.
Ramirez sits up, and Davis clubs him in the back of the head and neck illegally.
As Brown mentions that he needs to keep it clean, Davis wraps the choke arm under the chin again.
He tries a few times to complete the RNC, and Ramirez is wise to it every time by hand-fighting the right limb each time.
Ramirez turns to a knee and spikes Davis on his faceâthis is not legal eitherâand Davis one-arm chokes his opponent until the round ends.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Davis Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Davis Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Davis Round 2 Ramirez is the aggressor this round, shooting for a double-leg takedown 10 seconds in.
When Davis stuffs it, Ramirez drills a knee square in his chest.
Davis stands, cage wall behind him, and Ramirez lays into him with a damaging flurry of fists that buckle his knees.
Ramirez backs off and cracks him one last time before resetting, and the two get back to chopping at one another with kicks.
Davis recoils his leg after taking it hard on the calf, and Ramirez winds up and swings for the moon.
Davis knocks him back with a counter left, and he lets Ramirez plod forward so he can bust him in the chops.
Ramirez swings and misses, and Davis signals at him to come get some.
Ramirez obliges with winging punches, and Davis sees most of them coming and has his guard up.
Ramirez presses forward behind a right hand, and he takes a knee on the sternum in the process.
Ramirez lands on Davis, and Davis snaps his head back with the counter.
Davis goes to the body and head as he hurts Ramirez, but Ramirez is tough as can be and is still swinging mercilessly.
Davis is a sniper, digging strikes to the body when not bashing his foe in the head.
Ramirez backs off and loads up on a straight left hand, and Davis takes it and three more without flinching.
"Beast Boy" channels his inner beast mode and attacks the body several times before rocking Ramirez with head shots.
Ramirez shakes out the cobwebs and strikes the front leg, and he has a one-two behind it.Davis punches and kicks the liver, and he leaps at Ramirez with a knee that shakes him to his core.
Ramirez may be still on his feet, but he is no longer in the fight.
Davis unloads on him with a final barrage of power fists, crumpling Ramirez with his body shots and ending him with a right hand on the temple.
When Ramirez hits the deck, Brown intervenes.
Even spent, Davis found a way to push through his fatigue and get the stoppage.
The Official Result Mike Davis def.
Mitch Ramirez R2 4:08 via TKO (Flying Knee and Punches)
Kennedy Nzechukwu (238) vs.

Valter Walker (244.5) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Nzechukwu (-210); Walker (+150) Round 1 Having established himself in his new weight classes with two first-round knockouts in two appearances, Nzechukwu (14-5, 8-5 UFC) is ready to start taking bites out of the heavyweight leaderboard.
In a battle of unorthodox nicknames, "American Savage" will try to clean the nose of "The Clean Monster" Walker (13-1, 2-1 UFC).
The large gentlemen measuring nearly 13 feet in combined height will receive oversight from a man that can measure up physically in referee Eric McMahon.
A fist bump precedes the action, and one way or another, at least one heavyweight is getting finished tonight.
Is it during this one?
Both fighters want to have their foot on the outside, and Walker lumbers forward and runs with his hands down to take the fight down.
Nzechukwu gets blasted by a particularly fierce right hand, and Walker abandons the takedown to clobber him further with a flurry of fists.

When Nzechukwu is in a bad way, Walker stops striking, and looks to drag him down to the mat.He sells out to pull Nzechukwu's weight down in a sacrifice throw, but he uses what looks like a flop to the mat to snatch up an inverted heel hook.

Nzechukwu's face contorts in agony as his foot or ankle pops from the nasty submission, and he shouts out and taps at the same time to make sure that Walker will let go.He does just that, releasing the grip and standing to jump on top of the cage to celebrate.
"The Clean Monster" has just broken the nearly 120-day lull between heavyweight finishes, doing so with a brutal submission where it is surprising that Nzechukwu is able to stand under his own power.
That is three heel hooks in a row for Walker, putting him in rarified air across major organizations and heavyweights throughout the sport.
The Official Result Valter Walker def.
Kennedy Nzechukwu R1 0:54 via Submission (Inverted Heel Hook)
Lauren Murphy (126) vs.

Eduarda Moura (126) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Moura (-700); Murphy (+500) Round 1 Large age gaps are the name of the game tonight, as there is a solid number of fighters clocking in 10+ years older than their adversaries.
Elder stateswoman Murphy (16-6, 8-6 UFC), 41, is planning on calling it no matter the result of her final flyweight clash.
She battles a Brazilian in Moura (11-1, 2-1 UFC) who calls herself "Ronda" despite not celebrating a single armbar as a pro.
The women a decade apart in age will toe the line as referee Blake Grice watches on.
Ready to go, the flyweights clap hands before engaging.
Murphy puts a few jabs together to get started as "USA" chants boom in the building.
Moura retaliates but cannot find her range.
She lands a single low kick, and darts back to evade an overhand right.
Moura chops at the front leg again, and she stings the former title challenger with a guard-splitting right hand.
Murphy shoots in for a takedown, knocking Moura off her feet but landing in an awkward position that allows Moura to immediately stand.
The Brazilian hits her own takedown, and the moment Murphy hits her back, she is hand-fighting.
Murphy uses the two-on-one wrist control she finds to set up a kimura in an effort to sweep, but Moura breaks it up.
"Ronda" scores a few short ground strikes before lowering herself close in chest-to-chest position, flirting with an arm-triangle choke.
Murphy fights out of the choke and pushes off of her opponent with an upkick, making sure she does not strike with the sole of her foot and using it only to back Moura off.
Grice signals it was a legal maneuver, and Murphy bursts back to her feet and puts hands in Moura's face.
Moura fires back with a pair of overhand rights, and she stuffs a telegraphed takedown coming at her.
Murphy gets her jaw jacked when plodding forward, with Moura releasing a salvo of punches and concluding her combination with a chopping kick.
Moura darts in to smack Murphy with a shovel hook, and she follows with a one-two.
Murphy hurls a right hand back at her but misses the mark.
Moura beats her to the punch in exchanges, and her leg kicks continue to go unanswered.
Murphy follows her foe around and they trade punches until the round concludes.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Moura Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Moura Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Moura Round 2 The flyweights touch gloves to get started, and they pick up where they left off.
Moura does good work with her calf kick, Murphy is a little too slow in the hands and her face is getting chewed up.
The nose of "Lucky Lauren" is starting to turn a shade of red, and Moura strikes at the same spot again and again.
Murphy fires off a counter right hand, but it is one-and-done as anything else she lobs goes wide.
Moura pushes off a one-two and stuffs a takedown shot.
Murphy closes the distance in pursuit of a body lock takedown, but Moura's balance is solid and she tosses Murphy aside.
When Murphy resets, Moura bears down on her with powerful right hands.
Murphy again tries for a takedown, hoping her pressure is starting to wear Moura down.
Moura stays busy behind her jab, even driving her foe back with multiple combinations.
When Murphy presses in, Moura scoops her up with a double and plants her on her seat.
Murphy fights back to her feet using the wall, and Moura wants to drag her back down.
The Alaskan hacks at the side of the head with elbows when not fighting off the takedown, which transitions to a single.
Murphy breaks out of the clinch and goes after Moura, although she lands little more than a jab before the round concludes.
Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Moura Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Moura Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Moura Round 3 Moura wants to hug, but Murphy wants to fight.
This results in an odd moment where they don't know what to do.
After a few seconds, they decide it's time to start fighting again.
Moura fights.
Murphy fights back.
Murphy's forward pressure pushes back the younger Brazilian, but she is unable to land cleanly often.
Murphy slows Moura down with a takedown effort, bullying "Ronda" to the fending and wrangling her to the floor.
Moura sits up on her knees recklessly, head in the air, and Murphy wraps hold of a guillotine choke and has it tight.
Moura grabs hold of her opponent's shirt to get out of the submission, and Murphy still hangs on tight.
Using the choke to drag Moura back to her feet, Murphy cranks on it and drills Moura in the face with a knee.
Moura survives the submission and separates.
Murphy rushes after her spent opponent, with Moura taking deep breaths and backpedaling with little-to-no power on her strikes.
Murphy probes with her jab, and Moura keeps moving to not stay in one place for long.
Murphy crashes towards her and thinks about changing levels, but bails on it to throw hands.
The hands are largely inaccurate, and the one that to land are not particularly damaging.
Murphy relies on her jab, using it to partially set up a double.
Moura tosses her aside and smacks her foe with a scooping left.
Murphy presses the action with a minute left, swatting at her the Brazilian and walking into a few solid strikes.
Moura sticks a one-two down the pipe to force some swelling around the former title challenger's left eye, but Murphy pays it no mind.
Even when Moura cracks Murphy with a right hand, Murphy still meanders ever forward.
Moura appears to have gotten a second wind, and she connects cleanly on Murphy with a right hand to wobble her knees.
One last right hand from Murphy concludes the match, and an excited Moura dances her way to her corner, flexing all the way there.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Murphy (29-28 Moura) Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Murphy (29-28 Moura) Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Murphy (29-28 Moura) The Official Result Eduarda Moura def.
Lauren Murphy via Unanimous Decision (29-28, 29-28, 29-28)
Jake Matthews (170.5) vs.

Chidi Njokuani (170.5) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Njokuani (-150); Matthews (+125) Round 1 Don't look now, but Matthews (21-7, 14-7 UFC) is about to turn 31 and enter into his 22nd UFC appearance.
His assignment tonight is the brick-fisted ex-middleweight Njokuani (25-10, 1 NC; 5-3 UFC), who had issues making weight but still hit 170.5 after coming back within the extra hour allotment.
Knowing this one could last five minutes or five seconds, referee Jimmy Neely is prepped and ready for what's to come.
The fighters touch gloves.
Njokuani instantly capitalizes on his considerable reach advantage by letting fly a number of vicious kicks off the guard of his opponent.
One or two get through, and Matthews proves he has a chin on him early.

Njokuani fights Matthews back, and Matthews trips him to the mat and takes his back while Njokuani is on his knees.Matthews starts looking for a short choke from behind, and Njokuani stands up and leans against the cage to take some of the weight off of him.
"The Celtic Kid" clings to and changes his grip, keeping his forearm beneath the chin, and his rear-naked choke is tight as a tiger.

Njokuani nearly shakes Matthews off of his back, but with Matthews clinging on the side choking the life out of him, "Chidi Chidi Bang Bang" is forced to surrender.Matthews lets go and apologizes to Njokuani for finishing him, and calmly walks away to chat with announcer Bruce Buffer.
The Official Result Jake Matthews def.
Chidi Njokuani R1 1:09 via Submission (Rear-Naked Choke)
Max Griffin (170.25) vs.

Chris Curtis (170.5) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Curtis (-310); Griffin (+250) Round 1 One win away from getting his .500 UFC record back, Griffin (20-11, 8-9 UFC) will be staring across the cage from Curtis (31-12, 1 NC; 5-4, 1 NC UFC).

There are no more rules in MMA, as Curtis was able two weeks ago to violate one of the most seemingly inviolable rules of corner interference byoutright attacking his defeated fighter's opponentwithout so much as a whimper from the Nevada State Athletic Commission.
"The Action Man" was so starved for action that he recently crashed Luis Hernandez' victory party at Tuff-N-Uff 145, helping teammate Sean Strickland put hands on Hernandez.
It's time for these welterweights to bang it out with referee Justin Brown watching on.
They don't touch gloves.
Griffin springs after Curtis, pawing out short left hands that do not land.
This continues for about 30 seconds, until "Pain" releases a painful calf kick.
Curtis checks the second, and he eats a right hand down the pipe when countered.
Curtis lunges with a single left hand, pulling back to reset.
He stands still waiting for Griffin to come to him, suddenly releasing a pair of punches.
Griffin launches a low kick, clacking square into Curtis' cup loudly.
The crowd unleashes boos, possibly doubting he took the illegal blow, but the replay confirms the contact.
Brown gives Curtis time to recover, and after a minute, he is good to go.
Griffin pump-fakes several times with his legs, but no one is really actually engaging.
Curtis steps in to attack, and he complains to Brown that he was headbutted.
Brown tells him to fight on, blood flowing from the wound on Curtis' head, and Curtis is fired up.
He rushes at Griffin hurling punches, his vision partially obscured from the leaking head wound.
He strings three punches together, and Griffin snaps his head back and makes Curtis smile.
Curtis stalks after Griffin, enjoying himself now, and he takes a left hand so he can pound Griffin in the stomach and temple.
Griffin sticks him with a right hand, getting on his bike to move and stay off the gunnery range.
Curtis backs him to the wall, and Griffin springboards to get out.
Curtis pins him down with a few punches, and he is grappled by "Pain."
Griffin pushes him to the fencing, separating with seconds left and taking a knee to the jaw.
Curtis lashes out, grinning like a banshee, but nothing cleanly connects as the round concludes.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Griffin Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Griffin Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Griffin Round 2 The cut across Curtis' eyebrow is sealed between rounds, but it is deep and wide.
The two chatter at one another while trading hands, chasing one another around with momentum shifts.
Curtis drills Griffin with a right hook, and Griffin has to hurry to get away before taking further damage.
Griffin lets loose with a head kick that stuns Curtis, and as he tries to finish the job, Curtis nails him with a counter to put Griffin down.
Griffin jumps back up, and Curtis is on him, swinging harder and with meaner intentions.
The right hand from "The Action Man" splits a cut on the side of Griffin's left eye, and he swings at the same spot when lunging.
Griffin strafes to the side and looses a few punches to keep Curtis honest.
Curtis slips as he engages, but is no worse for wear.
Curtis misses a massive uppercut by a matter of inches, and he continues to march after the older fighter.
Curtis misses on a body kick, and he lands to put a right hand in Griffin's face.
Griffin kicks Curtis in the face, and Curtis completely ignores it but tells Brown that Griffin headbutted him again.
The clinch results in a stalemate, and the spoiled fans in the building start booing quickly.
The fighters trade knees when tied up before breaking apart, where Griffin gets off a one-two on the break.
Curtis goes right after him, headhunting all the while, and Griffin tags him with a right.
A second nearly stumbles Curtis, with his own strikes drawing no reaction from "Pain."
Griffin steps in to drive a shovel right hand to the torso, and Curtis grimaces and fires back with a knee.
He then activates a reaching combination of punches, with Curtis knocking Griffin back and off the wall.
They clinch up again, and Curtis catches him on the way out with a left hand.
They hurl fists at one another until the horn blares.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Curtis Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Curtis Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Curtis Round 3 Curtis introduces himself with a pair of tight jabs, using them to break up the big swings from the advancing Griffin.
Griffin fires right back, ending a salvo with a head kick that rebounds off the raised guard.
Curtis walks his man down, and Griffin tags him a few times on the way in.
Curtis ducks face-first into a right hand, and he takes a solid body kick that slips beneath his guard.
He walks Griffin down to stab him in the torso with a long punch, and he keeps swinging until Griffin knocks him back with a right hand.
The head movement from Curtis keeps him safe as he tries to remain in the pocket with his opponent, putting short combos together to decent effect.
Griffin looses a few body shots and a head kick, and Curtis retaliates with similar punches.
When Curtis ducks again, Griffin times a head kick, but it is the body shot of Curtis that is doing some damage.
Griffin backpedals, sucking wind a little, and Curtis lays into him with unanswered strikes.
Griffin ducks and counters one with a right hand over the top, and he tries to answer Curtis back with his firepower.
The short hooks do not have the same effect as Curtis' wide swings, but they are effective at keeping Curtis from walking over him.
Curtis lands with a hard right, and he finds his home with a left before Griffin tries to tie him up.
Griffin marches forward, and Curtis trips him to the mat and smiles at him from ear-to-ear.
It takes Griffin a moment to get up, and the two proceed to let one another have it.
Knees, head kicks and plenty of fists fly as they ride out the remainder of the clock waging battle.
Time expires, and they leave this in the hands of the judges.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Curtis (29-28 Curtis) Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Curtis (29-28 Curtis) Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Curtis (29-28 Curtis) The Official Result Chris Curtis def.
Max Griffin via Split Decision (28-29, 29-28, 29-28)
Junior Tafa (206) vs.

George Tokkos (206) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Tafa (-175); Tokkos (+140) Round 1 Down about 35 pounds with some serious physical transformation on his behalf, Tafa (6-3, 2-3 UFC) is aiming for a new lease on life at light heavyweight.
He will be able to trade with a willing dance partner in Tokkos (10-5, 0-2 UFC), where a knockout may not be guaranteed but it is greatly expected.
Before the bludgeoning, referee Eric McMahon clocks the fighters in, and they bump fists.
Tokkos says hello with a chopping low kick, and Tafa checks a second one and attacks behind his jab.
Tafa checks another kick, and he finds himself facing a single-leg entry from the Brit.
Tafa elbows the side of the head a few times, and Tokkos still manages to wrangle him to the floor.
Tokkos keeps hold of Tafa's left leg to trap him on the mat, and he holds in there.
Fans are not amused by the lack of activity of the two sluggers, and Tafa takes advantage of their momentum and stands up.
The Kiwi hacks down the back of the head a few times, grabs the fence and is still dragged to his seat courtesy of the Tokkos single.
Tafa wall-walks upright and is mat returned in a hurry.
Tafa stands, and he wraps up a power guillotine choke only to release it to slash down with elbows.
Tokkos throws Tafa back down to the floor with emphasis, and Tafa repositions himself to sit on his seat.
Tokkos smothers the former heavyweight with chest pressure, and McMahon tells them they need to do more than stall out.
Tafa gets to a knee, and Tokkos takes his back and loops one hook around the legs.
Tokkos dives after a short choke, and Tafa gives up his back and starts fighting hands.
Tokkos resets himself to set up a rear-naked choke, and he releases it to shift to full mount, arm-triangle briefly in play.
Tokkos postures up to drive down punches, getting warned for back of the head shots as well.
He continues to impose his weight on Tafa, and is warned for grabbing inside the glove to keep Tafa on the mat.
Tafa flips him over with seconds to go and lets Tokkos have it, cutting Tokkos on the top of the head as the horn sounds.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Tokkos Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Tokkos Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Tokkos Round 2 Tafa touches gloves with his foe and unleashes a hellacious overhand right.
Tokkos shrugs at him, but he is beaned by another big right.
Tafa clubs him with an uppercut, and Tokkos falls on his face.
Tokkos rolls around on the mat to try to get Tafa in a grappling exchange, and Tafa stands up and makes him get up.
Tokkos explodes forward, nailing Tafa with a shock right hand that he uses to set up a takedown after it.
Tafa gets dragged to the mat, and Tokkos clings to him and holds on with a front choke.
Along the way, he is warned for grabbing Tafa's gloves.
Tokkos steps over to half guard and easily climbs to three-quarter mount, only to pull himself back one step so he keeps Tafa flat on his back.
Tokkos sits up and drives down punches and hammerfists, and Tafa turns to his side to survive.
Tokkos quits punching for the most part to get a hook in around the side.
Tafa shifts to his back again, and Tokkos considers an arm-triangle choke and is admonished for eye gouging when he puts his fingers on Tafa's face.
Tokkos sits up again to land some bombs, and he uses the punches to set up a rear-naked choke.

Tafa on his side is able to break up the submission, but Tokkos is still on him making him carry every additional pound.This time, Tokkos advances to full mount, and he latches on with an arm-triangle choke and steps over to the side.
Crushing down with all of his energy, Tokkos forces Tafa to submit to the choke.McMahon breaks up the sub, and Tokkos strides away and drops to his knees to take in his first UFC victory.
The Official Result George Tokkos def.
Junior Tafa R2 4:25 via Submission (Arm-Triangle Choke)
Vitor Petrino (249) vs.
Austen Lane (245) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Petrino (-700); Lane (+500) Round 1 There are multiple themes for UFC Nashville: age difference and weight class shifts.

The latter is the case for light heavyweight expat Petrino (11-2, 4-2 UFC), who put on so much muscle that he actually weighs a few pounds more than career heavyweight Lane (13-6, 1 NC; 1-3, 1 NC UFC).
There was already a heavyweight finish tonight, so these two can hopefully keep the good vibes going.
Referee Jimmy Neely will be the third man in the Octagon, and he oversees a quick glove touch to open things up.
Absolutely nothing happens for the first 30 seconds, until Petrino finally breaks the silence with a leg kick.
Lane answers immediately with a one-two to the breadbasket.
The Floridian scores a few leg low kicks on the outside, staying out of range from anything that Petrino may be chambering.
Petrino catches a wayward kick, grabs hold of the limb and hurls Lane to the floor.
The Brazilian moves right into full mount like a hot knife through butter, and he sets up an arm-triangle choke but is in the wrong position to secure it.
Petrino stays heavy on top of his foe, not allowing Lane to budge more than an inch.
Petrino briefly flirts with a keylock, letting it go to find another opening.
Petrino switches his grip for the arm-triangle choke to the other side, and he tries to jump over to the side to complete it.
Lane fights off the first shift, but Petrino is squeezing down hard in mount.

"Icao" releases the choke and sits up to start swinging.Lane sways and moves as best as he can to avoid the strikes but turns too far one direction, and Petrino stops swinging to latch on with a rear-naked choke grip that is still on top of the chin.

The moment the CM System fighter slithers the arm beneath the chin, Lane taps out.Lane has suffered the first submission defeat of his career, while Petrino has announced himself as a heavyweight with zero plans on moving back down in weight.
The Official Result Vitor Petrino def.
Austen Lane R1 4:16 via Submission (Rear-Naked Choke)
Nate Landwehr (146) vs.

Morgan Charriere (146) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Charriere (-260); Landwehr (+210) Round 1 They may not be a decade apart, but Landwehr (18-6, 5-4 UFC) will check in close to eight years older than Charriere (20-11-1, 2-2 UFC).
This fun featherweight clash will be overseen by referee Blake Grice, and they bump fists.
The crowd is almost already on its feet in support of the Tennessee-based Landwehr.
Things do not start well for him, as he takes a number of heavy leg kicks, and when he fires one back, it is checked with an audible thud.
Both men whiff on haymaker right hands, and Charriere chew up the calf once again.
They trade low kicks, and Charriere's calf is already welted and swollen.
Charriere drills Landwehr upside the head and then goes low to the calf again, and the Frenchman is able to dart away from counters.
Landwehr just misses with a huge right hand, and he gets jabbed back.
Charriere jabs the body, hops away from the counter, darts back in to score and then lands a punishing low kick.
Landwehr swings mightily, but the hand speed of Charriere is beating him to the punch repeatedly.
Landwehr strides forward, putting three fists on the jaw of his opponent to shake him up.
"The Last Pirate" chops down the front leg and then shoots for a double.
Landwehr sprawls to nearly get up, but Charriere traps his foot to wrench him down.
Charriere gets the better of the grappling exchange, and he tries to body lock Landwehr down.
Landwehr turns to his knees, and Charriere is glad to take it and wrangle him around some more.
Landwehr keeps getting to his feet and leaning against the cage, but Charriere is a dog with a bone hunting for a takedown.
The Tennessean grabs hold of Charriere's neck to drag him down to the floor, and he holds him there until the horn sounds.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Charriere Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Charriere Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Charriere Round 2 The featherweights do not need more than a few seconds to start throwing down again.
Landwehr crowds his way in, attacking the body and then dropping to a knee.
He pops back up and sticks several jabs in the face of the Frenchman.
Landwehr loops a right hand around the guard, and scores his own left, but he still absorbs a calf kick at the end of it.
The two trade leather, neither overly concerned about the power of the other.
Charriere commits to a low kick, and his front kick bumps into the cup.
Landwehr tells Grice he wants to keep going, and motions to the crowd he is good to go.
He proceeds to throw everything he has in a right hand that makes him flying past his opponent.
He gathers himself, and both men blast one another in the chops.
Landwehr lands cleanly, is wide-eyed when he gets cracked back, and both men do not back down.
Charriere reaches with an overhand right, and he clips Charriere with a short left.
Charriere digs a kick to the body and then lead leg, and the American, empowered by "USA" chants, is loaded for bear.
He hits Charriere at least every time Charriere hits him back, and this results in a fun but measured series of striking exchanges.
Jaws get jacked, and Charriere circles away to find a better angle in.
Landwehr clubs his foe with a long string of punches, his work rate drastically increased from the previous round, and he shows it by landing cleanly on "The Last Pirate."
Landwehr takes a right hand flush and comes back swinging, catching Charriere with an uppercut and following it with two straight punches and two clubbing rights.
Technique may be flying out the window as Landwehr attempts standing hammerfists, and Charriere steps in with a powerful left hook on the cheek.
Both men connect flush on one another, and Landwehr steels himself to band it out to the bell.
Charriere gladly obliges him until Grice gets between them.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Landwehr Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Landwehr Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Landwehr Round 3 Landwehr sprints to the center of the cage, where he starts off with a fast flurry of fists.
Charriere unleashes a hellacious right hand directly behind the ear, and this staggers Landwehr.
Smelling blood, Charriere bombards "The Train" with a ferocious swarm of punches.Alternating power left and right hooks, Charriere can seemingly not miss as Grice takes a close look at the action.
Landwehr may only be on his feet with the fence behind him holding him up, and Charriere makes sure that will not be a factor with a thunderous right hand that bends Landwehr over.

One final concussive blow sends Landwehr hurtling to the ground, and the moment Landwehr hits the deck and is searching for a desperation single, Grice waves things off.Blood streams from Landwehr's nose, and he tries to campaign to Grice for the fight being restarted.
There is nothing left for anyone to do, as the match is over, and what a match it was.
The Official Result Morgan Charriere def.
Nate Landwehr R3 0:27 via KO (Punches)
Calvin Kattar (146) vs.

Steve Garcia (146) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Garcia (-120); Kattar (+100) Round 1 On a career-long four-fight skid, Kattar (23-9, 7-7 UFC) has not gotten his hand raised since outdueling Giga Chikadze in 2022.

Possibly in the later stages of his career at 37 years old, he is being matched up against a dangerous brawler in Garcia (17-5, 6-2 UFC) who is knocking on the door of ludicrous status should he clock "The Boston Finisher."
Referee Jason Herzog understands his assignment, and the fighters do too, as they touch gloves to engage.
The two featherweight strikers measure one another in the early going, with Garcia eventually leading the dance with a looping pair of punches and some awkward kicks to any target he can find.
Kattar ducks and swings hard on an overhand right counter that zips right past the Jackson-Wink representative.
Garcia is in the driver's seat but his connect rate remains low a minute in.
Garcia wraps a right around the guard, but his left goes wide.
Woots, whoops and cries rain down throughout the Bridgestone Arena, and Garcia silences them with a long punch combination and three head kicks in a row.
Kattar defends well but stumbles, and he gets back to his feet and takes a left hand on the jaw.
Garcia scores with a left hand and kicks after it.
Katter misses with a huge left hand, and Garcia races through it and lands a combination on Kattar's face.
Kattar is stuck not hitting anything of note, while Garcia is scoring to the head, body and legs.
Garcia spins with a sudden wheel kick, and Kattar shells up but his nose takes the brunt of it.
Kattar steps in with an elbow on the chin after Garcia hits him a few times, and he partially connects with a lead hook.
Garcia forces Kattar to constantly defend himself, and his power drives "The Boston Finisher" back a few steps.
Kattar starts to put his jab together, and he is answered with a Jackson-Wink-style oblique kick to the knee.
One more kick to the lead leg ends the tepid round.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Garcia Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Garcia Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Garcia Round 2 Both featherweights trade right hands as the round begins, and Garcia stays in Kattar's face but walks into a left hand on the jaw.
Garcia shrugs it off and bounces around before settling down, planting a one-two on Kattar's visage.
Kattar's looping punches continue to miss, as he is telegraphing his big right and Garcia is able to dodge or stay away from them.
Garcia walks Kattar down, spinning with a clean back kick to the ribs, and he drives home several rib-roasters as well.
This fires up Kattar, who cracks the favorite.
Garcia gives it right back, happy to be getting the brawl he was seeking.
Garcia beats Kattar to the jab time and time again.
Kattar employs a step-in elbow that graces Garcia's melon, and Garcia gives him back several body shots to think about.
Garcia dips and dodges the oncoming fire to crack Kattar with a huge left, smashing Kattar's nose and forcing Kattar to paw at it.
Garcia strikes the body when he sees an opening, and he skips forward to deliver two lefts on the chin.
Garcia misses a right and left hook by a matter of inches, and he kicks the front of Kattar's thigh to back him off.
The body work from Garcia is getting Kattar to drop his hands, and he winds up with a bomb of a left that buzzes past the longtime vet.
Garcia keeps doing work until the bell rings.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Garcia Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Garcia Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Garcia Round 3 Garcia immediately engages to start the last round, putting hands in Kattar's face early and often.
A heavy left hand drives Kattar back a ways, and he times a head kick and a spinning back fist that Garcia is able to defend.
Kattar hops back and forth switching stances, but he does not engage and is just backpedaling when Garcia comes at him.
Garcia reaches him with a left hand, and he loads up a subsequent bomb that nearly separates Kattar from his senses.
Kattar bounces off the fence to stay afloat, and he clinches Garcia to get his head right.
Garcia breaks off and chases the wounded man down, stabbing body kicks and following with liver punches that draw reactions almost every time he connects.
Garcia fearlessly walks "The Boston Finisher" down, hurling one-twos and any open strike he can lob.
Garcia tries for two clubbing lefts that do not get through, and he parries a front kick and pushes a left hand down the pipe.
Kattar appears to have recovered, but Garcia is not about to let him of the hook and hacks at him with a tomahawk elbow.
Garcia kicks Kattar's leg out, and he lets him back up to swing heavy leather.
Kattar bites down on his mouthpiece and walks into a left hand, and he spins with an elbow that bangs square into Garcia's temple.
Garcia, blood now streaking from the bridge of his nose, boots Kattar upside the head and follows him with a left hand.
He pushes Kattar back and pops him with a front kick, staying up close and looping lefts.
Kattar stands him up with a right hand, and he strikes with a knee and a spinning back fist that both get part of the betting favorite.
Garcia tosses windmills, and he waits for Kattar to spin so he can blast him when he plants.
Garcia lets loose with a head kick and a spinning wheel kick, and Kattar knocks him back with a fierce overhand right.
The two trade last strikes until time expires, and Garcia's knockout streak has officially ended.
Despite that, he still has soundly beaten a legitimate force at featherweight, and has announced himself as a new contender.

Calvin Kattar via Unanimous Decision (30-27, 30-27, 30-27)
Stephen Thompson (170.5) vs.

Gabriel Bonfim (171) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Bonfim (-380); Thompson (+310) Round 1 The final two battles will have the betting favorite of each 15 years younger than their respective underdog.
Former title challenger Thompson (17-8-1, 12-8-1 UFC) knows at the age of 42, his time at welterweight is running out.
Meanwhile, at 27, Bonfim (17-1, 4-1 UFC) is ready for his meteoric rise.
Depending on the Brazilian's strategy, a number of different types of fights could play out.
Like referee Blake Grice, we will see how this interesting stylistic clash plays out shortly.
They sportingly clap hands.
Thompson strikes first with a low calf kick.
He goes to the same spot again, and Bonfim answers him back three times.
They keep chopping at one another until Thompson kicks high.
Thompson tries a spin kick that buzzes past his target, and Bonfim stays composed working on the lead leg.
Bonfim brushes the side with a kick, and Thompson kicks him back much harder.
Bonfim is quick to get in and out with his speedy kicks, allowing him to dodge a side kick aimed at his face.
Thompson does not budge or flinch at what is offered at him, allowing Bonfim to chip away at his calf because it is primarily his only weapon.
Bonfim shoots, a full-throated double, and he grasps Thompson from behind, lifts him up and slams him down.
Thompson works his way back to his feet, and Bonfim chucks him right back down like a side of beef.
Bonfim starts to pursue a rear-naked choke, and he climbs on the back of "Wonderboy" and forces him to lower himself to a knee.
Bonfim only has a face crank, but he is squeezing with all of his might as he is still relatively fresh.
Thompson breaks free, and the crowd erupts as Thompson starts beating on Bonfim.
Bonfim still works his way back to his feet, ignoring the short knees aimed at his torso to lean on the karateka.
Thompson breaks out of the tie-up and grins, and he is quick to launch a head kick at the Brazilian.
Thompson walks his foe down, landing a body kick and potshotting him with distant strikes.
Bonfim reaches him with a left hook, and a second when Thompson is backing up wobbles Thompson briefly.
"Wonderboy" checks a calf kick, and he kicks high while Bonfim spins.
They collide legs together, and then smile and high-five as the round ends.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Bonfim Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Bonfim Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Bonfim Round 2 Bonfim forgets his mouthpiece between rounds, and he is able to replace it before they get started.
Thompson is able to stay at a safe enough range, just missing with a hook kick but scoring his calf kick.
Bonfim's head kick slaps off Thompson's hand, and he changes levels and shoots for a double, which turns quickly into a single.
Thompson defends by pushing off the fence and the back of Bonfim's neck to shut it down.
Thompson gets free, and he is free to kick before marching in with two straight punches.
He checks a kick, and a second lands.
Bonfim intercepts a blitzing Thompson with a hard left hook, but Thompson's chin holds up just fine as he digs a kick to the ribs.
Thompson kicks it a little higher to slam into the raised guard, and he dances out of the way of the swinging Brazilian.
Thompson is able to kick intercept his opponent, his hands still low as can be as he spins with a wheel kick.
Bonfim times a takedown shot, and it fails.
A second attempt allows Bonfim to get Thompson down for a second, but Thompson bounces back upright with the fence at his side.
Bonfim clings to his opponent and takes away all of his weapons, frustrating the crowd and his opponent equally.
Thompson frames off with his knee and gets out with 80 seconds to spare.
He jabs the body, avoids a left hook and comes back with his own overhand right.
Bonfim presses forward, walking into a side kick and taking a head kick clean on the side of the dome.
Bonfim takes it like a champ and keeps plodding forward, drilling Thompson in the chin with a stiff right hand.
Thompson shakes his head and spins with a kick that Bonfim sees coming.
Bonfim knocks Thompson off his feet with a left hand after kicking Thompson's shin so hard it splits open.
Thompson bounces off the floor and pushes through the pain to clobber Bonfim with a massive head kick.
Bonfim's balance nearly gives way, and he blasts him with a second to further hurt him.
Thompson tries to finish the job, and Bonfim desperately goes for a takedown he cannot get.
Before he gets his finish, the round ends.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Thompson Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Thompson Tristen Critchfield scores the round: 10-9 Thompson Round 3 The welterweights hug it out to get going, but the mean streak of Bonfim does not go anywhere.
Thompson kicks Bonfim in the head several times, slamming into the guard or the side of the head indiscriminately.
Blood pours out of the open wound on Thompson's shin, which leaves Thompson with a slight bloody footprint bouncing around the cage.
Bonfim tries to grapple his opponent, resulting in a clinch but no takedown.
Instead, he uses heel strikes to pound at the gash on "Wonderboy."
The commentary booth is not amused.
When they separate, Thompson looks at his shin and goes "whew," but promptly throws a head kick from that wounded limb.
Bonfim tries to stop the strikes from coming by going after another takedown, and Thompson breaks off much faster this time as he turns Bonfim around on the fence.
The karateka knows his best chance of victory is with his legs, and he brushes the Brazilian's hair with a wheel kick.
Thompson grins and Bonfim smiles back.
Thompson blasts Bonfim in the dome about as hard as one possibly can, and the Brazilian tanks it and even tries to offer back his own head kick.
Bonfim shoots for a double, putting Thompson on his seat as the crowd rejects his approach and lets him have it.
Bonfim hangs on to "Wonderboy" and takes an elbow on the side of the noggin for good measure.
Bonfim continues to cling to his adversary rather than do anything more with his position, and Grice asks for them to do something.
Thompson spins his man around for a second, but Bonfim is able to leverage him back to a knee.
Thompson hits a trip and nearly puts Bonfim down, and Bonfim stands and leans as the fight ends in the clinch.
It could go either way, which is something not too many people expected.

Derrick Lewis (261) vs.

Tallison Teixeira (259) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Teixeira (-270); Lewis (+225) Round 1 So far this year, Brazilians in UFC headliners are 0-8 against foreign adversariesâand for the sake of this math, Mackenzie Dern, born in Arizona once sporting a Valley Girl accent, is considered an American.
We won't get into the muddiness of "but Merab Dvalishvili has his American citizenship so technically he's an American male champ" because ain't nobody got time for that.
These two heavyweights sure don't.
If this goes the distance, a lot of parlay anchors will bust.
Lewis (28-12, 1 NC; 19-10 UFC) is hanging on to his all-time UFC knockout lead, and he can register one more at the expense of skyscraping Brazilian slugger Teixeira (8-0, 1-0 UFC).
Referee Jason Herzog will receive the final assignment of the evening, and he brings the big fellas together to bump their equally big fists together.
It's on with the show.
Teixeira moves himself to the center of the cage, and he blocks a head kick.
Teixeira catches him with a left hand directly on the eye socket, and Lewis clutches at it and appears compromised.

He might be playing possum, as Lewis unleashes fury in the form of a swarm of looping punches.Backing Teixeira off with a right, it is his nuclear left hand that sends the 6-foot-7 Brazilian flying down to the floor.

"The Black Beast" pounces, delivering a punishing barrage of ground-and-pound that knocks Teixeira's head around.Teixeira manages to stand up under fire, although he places every finger in the fence to pull on it as hard as he can to do so.
Herzog waves the fight off, and Teixeira pushes on Herzog's face and is upset about the possibly early stoppage.
The victorious Houstonian takes his shorts off, as has become his trademark, and he throws them out into the crowd.
He walks over to Teixeira's empty corner and mimes himself marking his territory like a beast.
He proceeds to remove his groin cup as well, pitching it deep into the audience as there is some fan that goes home with a sweaty, stinky souvenir.
Ever the classy gentlemen, he drops trou and moons the crowd.
He pulls them back up to march over to UFC chief Dana White, who hands him his cell phoneâit is President Donald Trump on the other end.
Lewis does not share which words were exchanged, but he does remark, "USA up in this hoe."
When commentator Daniel Cormier asks him what he wants next, Lewis deftly replies "my wife" and says she will be soon subjected to some heavy ground-and-pound.
What a guy.
When Lewis fights next, you best believe we will be here for it.
We hope you are too.
The Official Result Derrick Lewis def.
Tallison Teixeira R1 0:35 via TKO (Punches)
